  <p>
    Poetry in this archive is not a side project and not comic relief alone.
    It is compressed telemetry. When a system condition becomes too slippery for
    doctrine and too overgrown for a clean incident report, it sometimes survives
    as verse instead.
  </p>

  <h2>How to enter</h2>
  <p>
    Do not begin with the full haiku or limerick shelves unless you already know
    what seam you are following. Begin with family pages. Poetry makes more sense
    by neighborhood than by total corpus. A whole shelf of verse is weather;
    a family page is a pressure map.
  </p>

  <h2>Best neighborhoods</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Empathegy:</strong> where doctrine and incident residue keep leaking into verse.</li>
    <li><strong>Civic Benevolence:</strong> where parades, breakfasts, and scholarship optimism behave like policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Bin 8C and Mascot Affairs:</strong> where indexing infrastructure becomes poetic about itself.</li>
    <li><strong>Directive and forms verse:</strong> where managed absence and tri-directive stress get compressed into meter.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Recommended path</h2>
  <p>
    Start with a family page, not a pile. Bin 8C is a good first threshold because
    it is locally strange, tightly clustered, and already connected to both Lorelog
    and Mascot Registry. Empathegy is the second good threshold if you want the
    doctrine-versus-behavior split to stay visible while you read.
  </p>

